From: Jason Germino <jasongermino@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 07 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] usb: typec: tcpm: skip PS_SOURCE_ON timer in SRC_ATTACHED
 when Vbus already present

When a self-powered UFP (e.g. a DP display/monitor sourcing 5V on Vbus)
is connected, VBUS_PRES in the TCPC's POWER_STATUS register is already
asserted when SRC_ATTACHED is entered.

SRC_ATTACHED calls tcpm_src_attach() to enable the DFP's own Vbus
regulator, then unconditionally queues a PD_T_PS_SOURCE_ON (480 ms)
timer pointing back to SRC_UNATTACHED.  The intent is that
_tcpm_pd_vbus_on() — triggered by a POWER_STATUS interrupt on the
VBUS_PRES 0→1 edge — will cancel that timer and advance to SRC_STARTUP.

But when the UFP's Vbus is already present at 5V, VBUS_PRES never
transitions from 0 to 1, so the TCPC never fires the interrupt, and
_tcpm_pd_vbus_on() is never called.  The 480 ms timer always expires,
returning to SRC_UNATTACHED, and the port loops forever:

  SRC_ATTACHED → (480 ms) → SRC_UNATTACHED → TOGGLING →
  SRC_ATTACH_WAIT → SRC_ATTACHED → ...

Fix: after tcpm_src_attach() succeeds, check port->vbus_present.  If
already true, skip the timer and advance directly to SRC_STARTUP,
matching exactly what _tcpm_pd_vbus_on() would have done.

Signed-off-by: Jason Germino <jasongermino@gmail.com>
---
 drivers/usb/typec/tcpm/tcpm.c | 15 +++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 13 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/usb/typec/tcpm/tcpm.c b/drivers/usb/typec/tcpm/tcpm.c
--- a/drivers/usb/typec/tcpm/tcpm.c
+++ b/drivers/usb/typec/tcpm/tcpm.c
@@ -4036,8 +4036,19 @@ static void run_state_machine(struct tcpm_port *port)
 	case SRC_ATTACHED:
 		ret = tcpm_src_attach(port);
-		tcpm_set_state(port, SRC_UNATTACHED,
-			       ret < 0 ? 0 : PD_T_PS_SOURCE_ON);
+		if (ret < 0) {
+			tcpm_set_state(port, SRC_UNATTACHED, 0);
+		} else if (port->vbus_present) {
+			/*
+			 * Vbus was already present when we entered SRC_ATTACHED,
+			 * sourced by the self-powered UFP (e.g. a DP display).
+			 * VBUS_PRES in POWER_STATUS never transitions 0→1, so
+			 * _tcpm_pd_vbus_on() (which would normally cancel the
+			 * PD_T_PS_SOURCE_ON timer and advance to SRC_STARTUP)
+			 * is never called.  Advance directly.
+			 */
+			tcpm_set_state(port, SRC_STARTUP, 0);
+		} else {
+			tcpm_set_state(port, SRC_UNATTACHED, PD_T_PS_SOURCE_ON);
+		}
 		break;
